00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:44.250
This is purely an
illustration, but I

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:48.600
want to just talk about what's
behind this name drawdown.

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:50.430
To state the obvious,
climate change

00:05:50.430 --> 00:05:53.250
is caused by a rising
concentration of greenhouse

00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:54.990
gases in the atmosphere.

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:59.670
We hit 402 parts per million
of carbon dioxide last year

00:05:59.670 --> 00:06:00.930
and rising.

00:06:00.930 --> 00:06:04.680
Last time concentrations of
carbon dioxide were this high,

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:06.300
human beings weren't around.

00:06:06.300 --> 00:06:11.140
So we're very much living
in terra nova already.

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:14.370
So for us, we use
the term drawdown

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:19.380
to refer to the point in time at
which greenhouse gases could--

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:22.110
hopefully will--
peak and then begin

00:06:22.110 --> 00:06:25.570
to decline on a
year-to-year basis.

00:06:25.570 --> 00:06:27.300
So you hear a lot
in the climate space

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:31.290
about slowing emissions,
or stopping emissions,

00:06:31.290 --> 00:06:34.980
or stabilizing at
a particular level.

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:38.920
And when Paul and our team
stepped back and said,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:41.160
OK, if we're already
living in terra nova

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:44.850
at 402 parts per million,
the idea of stabilizing there

00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:48.150
seems a bit wacky.

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:52.650
Maybe that's where we'll end up,
but let's actually put forward

00:06:52.650 --> 00:06:56.940
a goal that is focused on
that tipping point where

00:06:56.940 --> 00:06:59.130
we then head back
towards conditions

00:06:59.130 --> 00:07:03.240
that are most conducive
for life on this planet.

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:06.750
So that's what
drawdown is about.

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:10.470
What we found as we
got into this work

00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:14.280
is that actually, human
beings have been hard at work

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:16.680
developing a plan
to achieve drawdown.

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:19.830
We just didn't realize that
that's what we were doing.

00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:23.550
So we've been out in backyards
and schools, fields, forests,

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:28.230
laboratories, companies,
communities, testing, learning,

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:30.390
refining, and then trying again.

00:07:30.390 --> 00:07:35.890
And along the way, as we've been
dabbling in climate solutions,

00:07:35.890 --> 00:07:38.850
there's been an incredible
body of data and peer reviewed

00:07:38.850 --> 00:07:42.210
research that has been
built up about these various

00:07:42.210 --> 00:07:43.710
technologies and practices.

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:48.930
So our job at Project Drawdown
wasn't to take a whiteboard

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:50.520
and invent a plan.

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:54.840
It was about going out and
codifying the collective wisdom

00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:58.260
that already exists in
humanity, the things

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:02.160
that we already know how to
do and we understand why they

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:05.180
work, why they don't work,
what their economics are,

00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:09.240
et cetera, et cetera, and
then to codify and synthesize

00:08:09.240 --> 00:08:14.910
that collective wisdom, and
then make projections using

00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:19.320
that incredible body of material
to understand how much can

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:27.170
solution x, y, or z move the
needle between now and 2050.

00:08:27.170 --> 00:08:31.370
Just the littlest bit more
of kind of context setting.

00:08:31.370 --> 00:08:33.559
Solutions are
solutions because they

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:36.480
do one or both of two things.

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:40.400
So they either avoid
sending greenhouse gases up

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:42.049
into the atmosphere,
whether that's

00:08:42.049 --> 00:08:44.360
through energy
efficiency, replacing

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:47.210
fossil fuels, or other,
more polluting technologies

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:51.260
with clean alternatives,
reducing consumption,

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:55.070
protecting land and
ecosystems, and/or

00:08:55.070 --> 00:08:59.270
they bring carbon dioxide back
home to earth through, turns

00:08:59.270 --> 00:09:01.940
out, the ultimate carbon
capture and sequestration

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:04.310
technology of photosynthesis--

00:09:04.310 --> 00:09:07.220
the world has actually already
really figured this out--

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:11.960
and bringing carbon back home
and storing it in plants, soil,

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:12.560
biomass.

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:15.470
So we often tend to get
into this trap of talking

00:09:15.470 --> 00:09:20.660
about carbon as bad, carbon as
evil, when actually carbon is

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:23.010
a fundamental and vital
building block of life.

00:09:23.010 --> 00:09:24.560
It's just a problem
of what we have

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:27.380
done with it, which is to
say, we've taken it from here

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:30.320
and we've sent too
much of it up there.

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:32.784
So the issue really is
about is about balance

00:09:32.784 --> 00:09:33.575
more than anything.

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:40.110
And then the solutions are
organized into sectors.

00:09:40.110 --> 00:09:43.650
So energy, food, women and
girls, buildings and cities,

00:09:43.650 --> 00:09:47.370
land use, transport,
and materials.

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:49.780
There are 80 solutions that
fall into these sectors,

00:09:49.780 --> 00:09:52.320
and you can think of
them as trains that

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:53.710
have already left the station.

00:09:53.710 --> 00:09:57.720
So they're technologies
and practices

00:09:57.720 --> 00:09:59.370
that we already see working.

00:09:59.370 --> 00:10:01.860
They're already growing,
they're already scaling,

00:10:01.860 --> 00:10:04.500
not everywhere, but
they are proven,

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:08.160
and they have potential
to grow significantly

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:13.600
and at a reasonable cost
over the next 30 years.

00:10:13.600 --> 00:10:15.600
And then we have 20
coming attractions.

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:19.530
So these are
technologies or practices

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:21.930
that are nascent,
they're evolving,

00:10:21.930 --> 00:10:24.960
maybe they're still
very much in R&amp;D.

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:28.560
And even if they are
being used effectively,

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:31.050
we don't have the
sufficient data from which

00:10:31.050 --> 00:10:32.580
to make the same
kind of projections

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:33.870
as we did for the other 80.

00:10:33.870 --> 00:10:37.290
So there's content in the book
about these coming attractions,

00:10:37.290 --> 00:10:40.500
but no numbers tied to them.

00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:43.800
Nonetheless, we're likely to
get some help from at least some

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:47.140
of these coming attractions
in the coming decades.

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:50.400
So if anyone is sort
of a betting type,

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:52.950
this would be a good
moment to jot down maybe

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:56.790
what you think the
top three sectors are.

00:10:56.790 --> 00:11:02.370
If you have the book in your
hand in this room, no cheating.

00:11:02.370 --> 00:11:04.240
But this is an interesting one.

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:09.030
We certainly have lots
of surprises on this.

00:11:09.030 --> 00:11:12.960
This is what a
solution looks like.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:16.480
This is number 69 of
80, electric bikes.

00:11:16.480 --> 00:11:21.680
This is a bicycle mechanic in
Berlin taking out his latest

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:23.680
e-bike model for a spin.

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:27.400
You can see that it combines
pedals and also a motor.

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:33.350
This portrait, I just
think, is beautiful.

00:11:33.350 --> 00:11:37.510
This is a Daasanach woman, which
is an ethnic group in Sudan

00:11:37.510 --> 00:11:38.950
and Ethiopia.

00:11:38.950 --> 00:11:41.260
She and other women
in her village

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:45.700
have started kind of gathering
bottle caps, SIM cards, sort

00:11:45.700 --> 00:11:49.450
of the detritus of 21st
century human civilization,

00:11:49.450 --> 00:11:52.840
and making these beautiful
headdresses and jewelry out

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:54.190
of them.

00:11:54.190 --> 00:11:56.830
This is the photograph that we
used for household recycling,

00:11:56.830 --> 00:11:59.135
which comes in at number 55.

00:12:03.230 --> 00:12:05.450
Number nine is
probably something

00:12:05.450 --> 00:12:08.180
that folks have not heard of.

00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:10.620
I had not.

00:12:10.620 --> 00:12:14.690
It's silvopasture, which comes
from the Latin words for forest

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:15.860
and grazing.

00:12:15.860 --> 00:12:18.110
So conventional wisdom
sort of tells us

00:12:18.110 --> 00:12:19.800
that trees and cows don't mix.

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:23.060
But actually, what we see
is that the integration

00:12:23.060 --> 00:12:27.200
of livestock and trees can
create incredibly resilient

00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:31.400
and symbiotic systems that
benefit farmers because they

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:34.910
have additional products
that are coming to market

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:36.260
at different timelines.

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:39.010
They're better
insulated from risk

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:41.540
in the face of drought or
extreme weather events.

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:44.570
When it comes to climate,
what's really powerful

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:48.290
is that if you compare a
pasture with trees to a pasture

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:51.230
without trees, the
pasture with trees

00:12:51.230 --> 00:12:53.840
sequesters five to
10 times more carbon

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:56.240
than its treeless brethren.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:59.960
So trees are kind of
the secret sauce here.

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:05.590
And this turns out to have
absolutely enormous potential.

00:13:05.590 --> 00:13:08.380
I'll just talk quickly
about the numbers

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:11.660
that you're seeing
on these slides.

00:13:11.660 --> 00:13:16.690
So in the upper right, you've
got the reduced CO2 emissions

00:13:16.690 --> 00:13:20.770
if this solution is scaled
vigorously but plausibly

00:13:20.770 --> 00:13:25.060
between 2020 and 2050.

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:27.020
If there are solutions,
which there are,

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:29.020
that address other
greenhouse gases--

00:13:29.020 --> 00:13:32.380
nitrous oxide,
methane, et cetera--

00:13:32.380 --> 00:13:34.900
then those impacts
are translated

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:37.070
into their equivalent
in carbon dioxide.

00:13:37.070 --> 00:13:40.190
So we're able to have an
apples to apples comparison

00:13:40.190 --> 00:13:42.236
and ranking of all of them.

00:13:42.236 --> 00:13:46.690
A gigaton-- probably this
is very evident at Google--

00:13:46.690 --> 00:13:50.440
a gigaton is a billion tons.

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:54.120
A cow weighs about a ton, so
this is a pretty good visual

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:55.810
for talking about this.

00:13:55.810 --> 00:13:58.030
So one gigaton is
about a billion cows

00:13:58.030 --> 00:14:00.430
worth of carbon dioxide.

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:06.640
For reference, we emitted
about 36 gigatons in 2016,

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:09.700
so about 36 billion cows worth.

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:12.250
So you can silvopasture
comes in just a bit

00:14:12.250 --> 00:14:15.920
below an annual
year's emissions.

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:21.180
That obviously
drives the ranking,

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:25.890
in this case number
nine out of 80.

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:28.770
And then in the
bottom left, you've

00:14:28.770 --> 00:14:32.640
got the incremental cost
to implement the solution.

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:35.820
So what's the additional
cost of purchasing

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:40.490
an electric vehicle as opposed
to a gasoline car, for example?

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:43.980
And in the bottom right,
the net operational savings,

00:14:43.980 --> 00:14:47.400
or, in a handful of
cases, cost over 30 years.

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:50.280
So again, what do
you save from driving

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:53.910
an electric vehicle as opposed
to driving a gasoline car?

00:14:53.910 --> 00:14:56.910
Or in the case of silvopasture,
what's the additional revenue

00:14:56.910 --> 00:15:00.240
that a farmer gets from running
a silvopasture operation as

00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:02.884
opposed to a regular
pasture operation?

00:15:05.730 --> 00:15:06.880
This is the top 20.

00:15:09.430 --> 00:15:14.050
There are, I think, some
really interesting insights

00:15:14.050 --> 00:15:18.220
and surprises, and some
things you would expect,

00:15:18.220 --> 00:15:20.170
and some really
unsung heroes that

00:15:20.170 --> 00:15:23.030
end up landing in this list.

00:15:23.030 --> 00:15:25.420
So I thought we might
just talk through what

00:15:25.420 --> 00:15:28.360
some of those things
are, and then we

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:31.630
can kind of come back to other
things if we don't cover them.

00:15:34.750 --> 00:15:37.360
The first thing that I think
is a really powerful ah-ha

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:41.620
from this work is that food is
eight of the top 20 solutions,

00:15:41.620 --> 00:15:44.530
and it's actually the largest
sector overall in terms

00:15:44.530 --> 00:15:47.800
of its potential impact.

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:52.270
Just a bit more than 320
gigatons of reduced carbon

00:15:52.270 --> 00:15:54.760
dioxide by mid-century.

00:15:54.760 --> 00:15:56.350
And what we include
in that sector

00:15:56.350 --> 00:15:59.710
is what we produce,
how we produce it,

00:15:59.710 --> 00:16:02.200
and then also reducing
waste so that we don't

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:05.800
have to produce so very much.

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:08.710
And that's where I think
maybe we should start.

00:16:08.710 --> 00:16:11.710
Reduced food waste, I
think, is pretty compelling,

00:16:11.710 --> 00:16:14.560
coming in at number three of 80.

00:16:14.560 --> 00:16:17.260
So about 1/3 of the food that
we produce around the world,

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:21.350
and about 40% in the
US, is not consumed.

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:27.610
And that excess food that's
then wasted generates about 8%

00:16:27.610 --> 00:16:29.570
of annual greenhouse
gas emissions.

00:16:29.570 --> 00:16:33.320
So it's really sizable
chunk of the pie.

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:36.280
In regions of high
income, we have a tendency

00:16:36.280 --> 00:16:37.920
to waste by choice.

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:39.910
So we overbuy.

00:16:39.910 --> 00:16:41.170
Portions are huge.

00:16:41.170 --> 00:16:43.780
We forget about leftovers
in the back of the fridge.

00:16:43.780 --> 00:16:47.770
Consumers and retailers
reject ugly produce.

00:16:47.770 --> 00:16:52.780
We have best by, sell
by, consume by labels

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:55.090
that actually, by and
large, are totally

00:16:55.090 --> 00:17:01.090
disconnected from safety, so we
throw perfectly good food away.

00:17:01.090 --> 00:17:03.400
In regions of lower
income, it tends

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:05.740
to be a question of
infrastructure and markets.

00:17:05.740 --> 00:17:10.310
So waste happens earlier
in the food chain,

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:12.609
if you will, and
it has a tendency

00:17:12.609 --> 00:17:18.130
to be related to storage
or labor, et cetera.

00:17:18.130 --> 00:17:21.880
What you see here in this photo
are ugly potatoes and carrots

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:26.260
that have been sent to the
rubbish heap in England.

00:17:26.260 --> 00:17:29.270
We invest a lot of
resources into food,

00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:30.910
whether we eat it or not.

00:17:30.910 --> 00:17:33.850
This is sort of stating the
obvious, but seeds, water,

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:37.750
energy, land, fertilizer,
labor, capital, on and on.

00:17:37.750 --> 00:17:41.560
We harvest it, we process
it, we ship it, we store it,

00:17:41.560 --> 00:17:48.190
we consume it, or we cook it,
perhaps, don't consume it.

00:17:48.190 --> 00:17:51.490
Sometimes we end up
cutting down forest

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:53.620
to grow more food
that we don't eat.

00:17:53.620 --> 00:17:57.220
And then oftentimes
that food ends up

00:17:57.220 --> 00:18:00.880
in a landfill, where it is
potentially generating methane

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:01.780
as it decomposes.

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:04.600
So you've got all of
these different dynamics

00:18:04.600 --> 00:18:07.150
of greenhouse gases
getting generated

00:18:07.150 --> 00:18:12.410
through this kind of
partial life cycle of food.

00:18:12.410 --> 00:18:15.640
And that's what makes this
such a huge opportunity.

00:18:15.640 --> 00:18:18.122
In France, pretty simple.

00:18:18.122 --> 00:18:20.080
They simply say it's
illegal for grocery stores

00:18:20.080 --> 00:18:21.610
to throw food away.

00:18:21.610 --> 00:18:23.200
So guess what?

00:18:23.200 --> 00:18:28.150
It ends up in the hands of
folks who need it and might not

00:18:28.150 --> 00:18:33.100
otherwise have it, or it ends
up being shoveled into livestock

00:18:33.100 --> 00:18:35.300
operations to feed livestock.

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:39.050
So lots of ways in to
impacting the solution.

00:18:39.050 --> 00:18:44.110
But I think what's really
exciting about this one coming

00:18:44.110 --> 00:18:47.020
in at number three is that
it's something we can all

00:18:47.020 --> 00:18:51.010
have an impact on immediately
and at no cost, which

00:18:51.010 --> 00:18:53.500
I think is pretty exciting.

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:57.170
And the same is true, actually,
of solution number four.

00:18:57.170 --> 00:19:00.640
This is a painting
some may recognize

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:04.150
of Vertumnus, who was the
Roman god of seasons and plant

00:19:04.150 --> 00:19:05.800
growth.

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:09.430
This solution is also completely
free and in our control,

00:19:09.430 --> 00:19:13.150
and we can adopt it the second
we walk out of the room, which

00:19:13.150 --> 00:19:15.280
is plant-rich diet.

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:19.600
So coming in at
about 66 gigatons,

00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:22.600
this is essentially doing the
math on Michael Pollan's advice

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:27.040
to eat food, not too
much, mostly plants.

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:31.270
Raising livestock
contributes about 1/5

00:19:31.270 --> 00:19:33.610
of our global emissions.

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:37.180
Ruminants-- cows, sheep--

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:39.730
are the most prolific offenders,
because they have a rumen.

00:19:39.730 --> 00:19:43.060
And They have a second stomach
in which cellulose ferments

00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:47.200
and it creates methane, which
mostly comes out as burps,

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:50.380
contrary to popular opinion.

00:19:50.380 --> 00:19:53.110
If cattle were their
own nation, they

00:19:53.110 --> 00:19:56.980
would be the third largest
emitter after China and the US.

00:19:56.980 --> 00:20:00.670
So this is no small problem.

00:20:00.670 --> 00:20:03.010
Some have probably
seen in the last week

00:20:03.010 --> 00:20:06.610
the article that came out in
"The Atlantic" and elsewhere

00:20:06.610 --> 00:20:12.070
that if Americans were simply
to swap beans for beef,

00:20:12.070 --> 00:20:16.690
we could reach up to
3/4 of our targets

00:20:16.690 --> 00:20:20.530
under the Paris
Agreement by 2020.

00:20:20.530 --> 00:20:22.120
No technology required.

00:20:22.120 --> 00:20:26.320
This is powerful stuff.

00:20:26.320 --> 00:20:29.150
Of course, dietary
change is hard.

00:20:29.150 --> 00:20:31.720
It's cultural and it's personal.

00:20:31.720 --> 00:20:35.970
I'm from the south, and nobody
wants to give up barbecue.

00:20:35.970 --> 00:20:39.960
So we did not model here
world becoming vegan.

00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:46.290
What we modeled here was animal
protein and calorie consumption

00:20:46.290 --> 00:20:49.260
coming down in
places like the US,

00:20:49.260 --> 00:20:51.420
where it's much too
high, and actually,

00:20:51.420 --> 00:20:53.850
calories and protein going
up in parts of the world

00:20:53.850 --> 00:20:55.840
where malnutrition is an issue.

00:20:55.840 --> 00:20:58.050
So this is more
about the whole world

00:20:58.050 --> 00:21:01.200
coming into a healthier
diet that ends up also,

00:21:01.200 --> 00:21:05.100
of course, having the benefits
of lowering chronic disease

00:21:05.100 --> 00:21:07.470
and health care
costs, et cetera.

00:21:07.470 --> 00:21:09.600
It also includes in
this number the impact

00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:11.760
of avoided deforestation
that would otherwise

00:21:11.760 --> 00:21:15.645
happen to grow more corn and
soybeans to feed more cows.

00:21:19.810 --> 00:21:23.580
Energy comes in with
five of the top 20.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:27.560
It's the second
largest sector overall.

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:29.870
And what I think is really
fascinating here, and worth

00:21:29.870 --> 00:21:32.900
pausing on, is that
energy has the tendency

00:21:32.900 --> 00:21:35.570
to just dominate our
conversations about climate

00:21:35.570 --> 00:21:36.620
change.

00:21:36.620 --> 00:21:39.440
In large part, that's because
energy has caused so very

00:21:39.440 --> 00:21:42.560
much of the problem,
and it may continue

00:21:42.560 --> 00:21:47.780
to do so if we don't get a
grip on fossil fuel emissions.

00:21:47.780 --> 00:21:50.990
So changing energy
sources and energy systems

00:21:50.990 --> 00:21:52.520
is absolutely critical.

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:55.670
But we would be remiss to
think that if we do that,

00:21:55.670 --> 00:21:58.130
we sort of have a hall
pass into the 22nd century.

00:21:58.130 --> 00:22:02.810
Even if we got to 100% renewable
energy, it cannot, by itself,

00:22:02.810 --> 00:22:04.590
solve global warming.

00:22:04.590 --> 00:22:09.680
So I think that's really
important context.

00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:11.140
I love this photo so much.

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:15.740
This is an Uru family that
lives on Lake Titicaca.

00:22:15.740 --> 00:22:17.810
You can see just
a little bit here.

00:22:17.810 --> 00:22:20.360
They live on a reed island.

00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:23.810
And they've just gotten
this solar panel, which

00:22:23.810 --> 00:22:25.340
means that they'll
have electricity

00:22:25.340 --> 00:22:27.710
at their home for
the first time,

00:22:27.710 --> 00:22:30.650
and the girls will not
have to do their homework

00:22:30.650 --> 00:22:32.860
by kerosene lamp anymore.

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:35.120
So you can imagine
kerosene lamps

00:22:35.120 --> 00:22:40.340
in a reed house on a reed
island is not a great recipe.

00:22:40.340 --> 00:22:43.940
So this is rooftop
solar, which, of course,

00:22:43.940 --> 00:22:47.840
has incredible potential
in higher income

00:22:47.840 --> 00:22:49.320
parts of the world.

00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:52.490
But as a form of
distributed energy,

00:22:52.490 --> 00:22:55.400
it has incredible potential
for the 1.1 billion people

00:22:55.400 --> 00:22:57.950
that don't have
access to electricity

00:22:57.950 --> 00:22:59.220
or an electric grid.

00:22:59.220 --> 00:23:02.510
So this is sort of one of
those great examples where

00:23:02.510 --> 00:23:06.890
there are just layers and
layers of positive co-benefits

00:23:06.890 --> 00:23:13.220
in these solutions, greenhouse
gases just being one of those.

00:23:13.220 --> 00:23:15.770
This one's also, I
think, really incredible.

00:23:15.770 --> 00:23:18.530
You see the potential
savings in home energy costs

00:23:18.530 --> 00:23:22.130
over 30 years of
almost $3.5 trillion.

00:23:22.130 --> 00:23:26.720
So again, another great
example of where economics

00:23:26.720 --> 00:23:31.100
are taking off and are
really going to push forward

00:23:31.100 --> 00:23:32.750
the scaling of these solutions.

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:38.020
Three of the top
20 solutions fall

00:23:38.020 --> 00:23:42.330
into what we call land use,
so non-agricultural land use.

00:23:42.330 --> 00:23:44.160
And these are solutions
that are focused

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:48.450
on restoring, protecting,
and harnessing

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:54.490
the power of land and ecosystems
for carbon sequestration.

00:23:54.490 --> 00:23:58.150
We're really just going through
a lot of my personal favorites

00:23:58.150 --> 00:23:59.910
from the book.

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:01.930
Anyone have a guess
on what this might be?

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:08.420
This is a harvested peatland.

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:12.500
So peatlands are
wetland ecosystems.

00:24:12.500 --> 00:24:15.680
We also call them bonds, mires.

00:24:15.680 --> 00:24:19.880
They are just 3% of
the world's land area,

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:22.460
but they're second only to
oceans in the amount of carbon

00:24:22.460 --> 00:24:23.570
that they store.

00:24:23.570 --> 00:24:27.240
And they hold twice as much
as all of the worlds forests.

00:24:27.240 --> 00:24:31.400
So peatlands need
some love, you know?

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:33.620
They are essentially
made of layers and layers

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:37.440
and layers and layers of
decomposing plant material.

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:40.010
So that's where you
get all of the carbon.

00:24:40.010 --> 00:24:42.320
If you left peat alone for
long enough under the right

00:24:42.320 --> 00:24:43.694
conditions, it
would become coal.

00:24:45.784 --> 00:24:47.700
When we were working on
the book, it was like,

00:24:47.700 --> 00:24:52.490
how do we give peatllands
some sparkle and some magic?

00:24:52.490 --> 00:24:55.130
It turns out that
the Irish poet Seamus

00:24:55.130 --> 00:24:57.240
Heaney has written a bunch of--

00:24:57.240 --> 00:25:01.340
wrote, I guess, in the 60s--
some really fabulous poems

00:25:01.340 --> 00:25:04.760
about bog land in Ireland.

00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:06.860
And he describes, in
one of these poems,

00:25:06.860 --> 00:25:11.152
"the ground itself is kind black
butter", which sort of then,

00:25:11.152 --> 00:25:12.860
all of a sudden, tells
you everything you

00:25:12.860 --> 00:25:15.260
need to know about peatlands.

00:25:15.260 --> 00:25:17.360
That kind black
butter makes them

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:22.600
under threat from farming
and forestry and fire.

00:25:22.600 --> 00:25:24.350
So what we've looked
at here is the impact

00:25:24.350 --> 00:25:27.140
of expanding the acreage
of protected peatlands.

00:25:27.140 --> 00:25:31.100
Again, we're not talking about
a huge amount of land area,

00:25:31.100 --> 00:25:35.420
but it's a lot of bang for your
buck in terms of protection.

00:25:35.420 --> 00:25:37.370
And what's also on this
slide that you haven't

00:25:37.370 --> 00:25:41.180
seen on others,
this 1,230 gigatons,

00:25:41.180 --> 00:25:44.120
that would be the
protected stock of carbon

00:25:44.120 --> 00:25:48.800
that the world's peatlands would
then hold as of mid-century.

00:25:48.800 --> 00:25:52.040
So another important
piece of the puzzle.

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:03.410
The number one solution
is refrigeration.

00:26:03.410 --> 00:26:07.080
Sort of deeply unsexy,
I'm sorry to say.

00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:13.920
It focuses on chemical
refrigerants in our AC systems,

00:26:13.920 --> 00:26:16.740
our refrigerators,
our cold chains.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:22.500
Folks probably remember that
in 1987, the Montreal Protocol

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:26.290
began to phase out of
chlorofluorocarbons, CFCs,

00:26:26.290 --> 00:26:29.200
which were, at that time, the
dominant chemical refrigerant

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:30.600
that we used.

00:26:30.600 --> 00:26:34.920
Their primary replacement
chemical, HFCs, great,

00:26:34.920 --> 00:26:37.740
on the one hand because they
have almost no negative impact

00:26:37.740 --> 00:26:39.220
on the ozone layer.

00:26:39.220 --> 00:26:43.950
But they turn out to be 1,000
or more times as powerful

00:26:43.950 --> 00:26:47.200
as carbon dioxide in terms of
their global warming potential.

00:26:47.200 --> 00:26:53.040
So solve one problem, end
up contributing to another.

00:26:53.040 --> 00:26:55.170
Last year, the world
came to an agreement

00:26:55.170 --> 00:26:59.100
to amend the Montreal Protocol
so the phase-out of HFCs

00:26:59.100 --> 00:27:02.310
is going to be coming first
in higher income countries,

00:27:02.310 --> 00:27:05.280
and then in a couple
of subsequent waves.

00:27:05.280 --> 00:27:07.260
Scientists think
that that move alone

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:10.450
could reduce global warming
by half a degree Celsius.

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:13.657
So this is no small thing.

00:27:13.657 --> 00:27:15.240
And what we've looked
at in this model

00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:19.350
is the potential to manage
the HFCs that are already

00:27:19.350 --> 00:27:22.800
in circulation and that will
come into circulation even

00:27:22.800 --> 00:27:25.950
as the world moves towards
and through phase-out.

00:27:25.950 --> 00:27:28.890
So basically addressing
leaks and managing

00:27:28.890 --> 00:27:31.960
what you do with these chemicals
at the point of disposal,

00:27:31.960 --> 00:27:34.500
which is when about
90% of emissions occur.

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:38.040
So really, really powerful.

00:27:38.040 --> 00:27:40.770
Again, because of that high
global warming potential

00:27:40.770 --> 00:27:42.390
in terms of carbon
equivalent, this

00:27:42.390 --> 00:27:47.070
comes in very high at almost 90
gigatons of avoided emissions.

00:27:50.210 --> 00:27:54.910
This is a section that has
surprised a lot of folks, women

00:27:54.910 --> 00:27:56.060
and girls.

00:27:56.060 --> 00:27:58.960
Solutions number six and seven,
educating girls and family

00:27:58.960 --> 00:27:59.890
planning.

00:27:59.890 --> 00:28:02.140
These are essentially
solutions that

00:28:02.140 --> 00:28:05.860
focus on advancing women's
rights and opportunity

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:08.770
and well-being, and then
the positive ripple effects

00:28:08.770 --> 00:28:13.540
that come out of that in terms
of the planet, of emissions,

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:17.560
but also lots of other
positive societal effects.

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:20.230
So what we've looked
at here is the impact

00:28:20.230 --> 00:28:24.220
of closing the gaps that
exist in the world on access

00:28:24.220 --> 00:28:27.680
to education and access to
voluntary family planning.

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:30.220
So this is really a solution
that begins and ends

00:28:30.220 --> 00:28:33.160
with rights, and then
the emissions impacts

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:34.210
are side effects.

00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:39.690
This is just another, I
think, really beautiful photo.

00:28:39.690 --> 00:28:44.100
This is a young girl who
is in school in Kenya.

00:28:44.100 --> 00:28:48.240
But 130 million girls around the
world are not in school today,

00:28:48.240 --> 00:28:52.350
and that's especially a problem
in secondary classrooms.

00:28:52.350 --> 00:28:54.840
Of course, education
is an intrinsic right,

00:28:54.840 --> 00:28:56.700
and it feels very
obvious to say,

00:28:56.700 --> 00:29:01.710
but it lays an absolutely
vital foundation for our lives.

00:29:01.710 --> 00:29:04.290
So what we see with
more education is

00:29:04.290 --> 00:29:07.080
that women have higher
wages and better

00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:11.040
upward mobility, maternal
and infant mortality go down,

00:29:11.040 --> 00:29:14.480
rates of HIV, AIDS,
and malaria go down.

00:29:14.480 --> 00:29:15.900
Farms are more productive.

00:29:15.900 --> 00:29:17.970
They're less likely to
be forced into marriage.

00:29:17.970 --> 00:29:20.430
On and on and on and on and on.

00:29:20.430 --> 00:29:26.430
It also turns out that women
who have more years of education

00:29:26.430 --> 00:29:28.800
choose to have fewer
children, more actively

00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:31.680
engage in the use
of contraception,

00:29:31.680 --> 00:29:33.360
and their children
are healthier.

00:29:33.360 --> 00:29:36.840
So if you look at a woman
who has no years of schooling

00:29:36.840 --> 00:29:38.280
compared to 12
years of schooling,

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:42.270
the difference is four to
five children per woman.

00:29:42.270 --> 00:29:44.670
I think it's really,
really important

00:29:44.670 --> 00:29:48.261
to be clear that in the
poorest countries in the world,

00:29:48.261 --> 00:29:50.760
and in parts of the world where
girls are having the hardest

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:52.950
time getting
educated, per capita

00:29:52.950 --> 00:29:55.770
greenhouse gas emissions
are very, very low.

00:29:55.770 --> 00:29:59.730
They are a fraction of
what they are in the US

00:29:59.730 --> 00:30:01.860
and in parts of the world
that have done the most

00:30:01.860 --> 00:30:03.720
to cause the problem
of global warming

00:30:03.720 --> 00:30:06.280
and have the most work
to do to address it.

00:30:06.280 --> 00:30:10.620
So these absolutely have to
be seen in the context of all

00:30:10.620 --> 00:30:12.810
of these other solutions.

00:30:12.810 --> 00:30:16.750
But still, when you're talking
about changes in fertility

00:30:16.750 --> 00:30:18.880
rates, you're talking
about a difference

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:21.710
in the number of feet making
their carbon footprints

00:30:21.710 --> 00:30:23.930
as of mid-century.

00:30:23.930 --> 00:30:27.014
And when you add that up, the
cumulative effect is powerful.

00:30:27.014 --> 00:30:28.930
So what we've looked at
here is the difference

00:30:28.930 --> 00:30:32.500
between hitting the
UN's high population

00:30:32.500 --> 00:30:37.190
projection as opposed to its
medium population projection.

00:30:37.190 --> 00:30:40.300
And that difference is
essentially all comes down

00:30:40.300 --> 00:30:42.110
to family planning.

00:30:42.110 --> 00:30:44.500
Education and then
contraception or are

00:30:44.500 --> 00:30:50.680
two components that really
add up to drive that impact.

00:30:50.680 --> 00:30:52.870
It also turns out
that education is

00:30:52.870 --> 00:30:56.570
really powerful for shoring up
resilience to climate impacts.

00:30:56.570 --> 00:30:58.810
So this is another
one of the solutions

00:30:58.810 --> 00:31:01.850
that has kind of many, many,
many layers of benefits.

00:31:01.850 --> 00:31:07.420
So for example, education
is the number one factor

00:31:07.420 --> 00:31:11.000
for girls and women
surviving natural disasters.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.480
So more education,
you're less likely to be

00:31:13.480 --> 00:31:16.430
injured or displaced or
killed when a storm hits.

00:31:16.430 --> 00:31:19.270
And that's obviously just
one of the many impacts

00:31:19.270 --> 00:31:21.380
that's headed our way
with climate change,

00:31:21.380 --> 00:31:23.300
even as we work to address it.

00:31:23.300 --> 00:31:25.990
So if you add up educating
girls and family planning,

00:31:25.990 --> 00:31:28.390
it turns out that actually
empowering women and girls

00:31:28.390 --> 00:31:30.430
is the number one solution
to global warming.

00:31:35.860 --> 00:31:39.310
Despite this being
the era of Buzzfeed,

00:31:39.310 --> 00:31:41.230
it is not actually
about the number one

00:31:41.230 --> 00:31:44.560
or the top five or the top 10.

00:31:44.560 --> 00:31:47.020
We need all of these
solutions, and we

00:31:47.020 --> 00:31:49.640
have all of these solutions.

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:53.200
So I just want to zip
through a few more photos

00:31:53.200 --> 00:31:57.530
