00:32:20.530 --> 00:32:24.390
Farm, which is 88 turbines off
the coast of Norfolk, England.

00:32:24.390 --> 00:32:25.720
This is not photo-shopped.

00:32:25.720 --> 00:32:28.125
This is actually an
athlete in training.

00:32:32.390 --> 00:32:37.550
We can install more green
roofs and cool roofs.

00:32:37.550 --> 00:32:39.780
This one, I think, is
particularly lovely

00:32:39.780 --> 00:32:41.900
overlooking Basel, Switzerland.

00:32:41.900 --> 00:32:43.610
This is the roof of
the hospital there.

00:32:48.140 --> 00:32:53.120
We can spread a set of
actually very simple practices

00:32:53.120 --> 00:32:56.990
for growing rice in a way
that increases yields but also

00:32:56.990 --> 00:33:00.710
reduces methane production
through the growing

00:33:00.710 --> 00:33:02.180
cycle of rice.

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:06.650
And then, as I
mentioned earlier,

00:33:06.650 --> 00:33:08.990
we will have some help
from coming attractions.

00:33:08.990 --> 00:33:12.040
So this is one that we are
already getting help from.

00:33:12.040 --> 00:33:15.190
I think we'll see the
first high rise wood

00:33:15.190 --> 00:33:17.200
building in Portland, Oregon.

00:33:17.200 --> 00:33:22.740
It's been permitted and I
think construction has started.

00:33:22.740 --> 00:33:24.530
I'm just think this
one is so fascinating.

00:33:24.530 --> 00:33:30.070
So there are now these high
performance wood products

00:33:30.070 --> 00:33:34.690
that are as strong, and
even more fire resistant,

00:33:34.690 --> 00:33:39.209
than steel and concrete, which
I found just wild and shocking.

00:33:39.209 --> 00:33:40.000
Go read about this.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:42.080
It really is quite amazing.

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:46.500
And they have the double
benefit of sequestering carbon

00:33:46.500 --> 00:33:47.390
in that wood.

00:33:47.390 --> 00:33:49.760
Dry wood is about 50% carbon.

00:33:49.760 --> 00:33:54.040
So if you've got
wood that's locked

00:33:54.040 --> 00:33:56.710
into the structure
of a building that's

00:33:56.710 --> 00:33:58.960
going to stand for a
long time, that carbon

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:00.760
is being held there.

00:34:00.760 --> 00:34:03.250
And also you're able
to avoid the emissions

00:34:03.250 --> 00:34:06.580
of steel and concrete,
which are incredibly high.

00:34:06.580 --> 00:34:09.487
Combined, they're at least
10% of our annual emissions.

00:34:09.487 --> 00:34:10.570
So really, really amazing.

00:34:14.010 --> 00:34:15.139
This is just another--

00:34:15.139 --> 00:34:17.540
now I'm just showing you
guys a couple cool ones

00:34:17.540 --> 00:34:19.699
because I think they're fun.

00:34:19.699 --> 00:34:22.909
We might be able to use
marine permaculture arrays.

00:34:22.909 --> 00:34:26.719
So imagine sort of giant
lattice-like structures

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:30.110
from which we can grow
floating kelp forests that

00:34:30.110 --> 00:34:33.380
have the benefit of
sequestering carbon really

00:34:33.380 --> 00:34:37.909
quickly, but also creating
habitat for fish and sea life

00:34:37.909 --> 00:34:40.100
in parts of the oceans
where basically they're

00:34:40.100 --> 00:34:43.280
now sort of dead
zones, potentially

00:34:43.280 --> 00:34:45.260
producing food and fuel.

00:34:45.260 --> 00:34:47.389
There's a lot of exciting
opportunity here.

00:34:49.969 --> 00:34:52.489
Maybe we will end up
pursuing the proposal

00:34:52.489 --> 00:34:55.159
of a pair of father
son scientists

00:34:55.159 --> 00:34:59.900
in Siberia who are
testing and advocating

00:34:59.900 --> 00:35:04.610
for repopulating the
Arctic with herbivores,

00:35:04.610 --> 00:35:07.660
perhaps even
recreated mammoths--

00:35:07.660 --> 00:35:09.710
there are folks also
working on this--

00:35:09.710 --> 00:35:14.140
that could prevent
permafrost from melting.

00:35:14.140 --> 00:35:15.890
I'll let you read
about that in the book

00:35:15.890 --> 00:35:19.070
because it's quite fun.

00:35:19.070 --> 00:35:21.680
I think you can look
at these 100 solutions

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:26.700
and think, oh my gosh,
we have so much to do.

00:35:26.700 --> 00:35:30.260
But you can also look at them,
I think, and see, oh my gosh,

00:35:30.260 --> 00:35:32.000
there's so much we can do.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:35.000
There are literally so many
ways into having an impact

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.310
on this issue, so
many footholds,

00:35:37.310 --> 00:35:42.050
and so many realms of agency
for literally everyone, which

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:44.270
I think is really,
really exciting.

00:35:44.270 --> 00:35:48.250
The toolbox that we have
is already so, so, so rich.

00:35:51.620 --> 00:35:54.320
We started with
this dominant story

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:56.822
arc of doom and
gloom, the one that

00:35:56.822 --> 00:35:59.030
tells us that human beings
are terrible, horrible, no

00:35:59.030 --> 00:36:01.250
good, very bad.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:05.280
When you come through
this lens of solutions,

00:36:05.280 --> 00:36:06.830
the other side of
the story, I think,

00:36:06.830 --> 00:36:13.640
becomes really clear, which
is that human beings are also

00:36:13.640 --> 00:36:18.350
creative and compassionate and
collaborative and committed,

00:36:18.350 --> 00:36:22.490
and every now and again,
brilliant and pretty gutsy.

00:36:22.490 --> 00:36:25.700
And I think if we want
to stay courageous

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:27.950
and driven in the face
of climate change, which

00:36:27.950 --> 00:36:31.220
we need to do, and if we
want to invite more people

00:36:31.220 --> 00:36:33.440
into this work,
which we need to do,

00:36:33.440 --> 00:36:36.560
then I think we need to hear
and tell and own that story.

00:36:36.560 --> 00:36:40.100
The doom and gloom at higher
and higher volume and frequency

00:36:40.100 --> 00:36:44.720
is not exactly a
great pickup line.

00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:46.380
And this is a true story.

00:36:46.380 --> 00:36:50.190
It's a story of what we are
already doing, what we can do,

00:36:50.190 --> 00:36:54.834
and I think, also, about
who we are as human beings.

00:36:54.834 --> 00:36:56.750
The climate movement
basically has been giving

00:36:56.750 --> 00:37:02.600
and I have a nightmare speech
for the last 30 or 40 years.

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:04.670
It's a really easy
speech to give, actually,

00:37:04.670 --> 00:37:07.490
when you look at the science of
the problem and the timelines

00:37:07.490 --> 00:37:08.630
that we're on.

00:37:08.630 --> 00:37:14.390
Screaming "I have a nightmare",
really doable and reasonable.

00:37:14.390 --> 00:37:18.830
But it's not working
as a strategy.

00:37:18.830 --> 00:37:21.770
We need the clear and credible
vision that's actually worth

00:37:21.770 --> 00:37:23.330
fighting for.

00:37:23.330 --> 00:37:26.810
What are we talking about
beyond inverting catastrophe?

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:29.530
What's the dream?

00:37:29.530 --> 00:37:33.170
And I'm very, very
hopeful that drawdown

00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:36.140
begins to help
articulate that vision,

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:39.530
makes a contribution
towards that vision.

00:37:39.530 --> 00:37:41.750
For me personally,
it's a vision that's

00:37:41.750 --> 00:37:45.860
grounded in honoring
the sacredness of life,

00:37:45.860 --> 00:37:48.095
human and non-human
life, on this planet.

00:37:50.600 --> 00:37:54.110
The solutions for
reducing greenhouse gases

00:37:54.110 --> 00:37:58.430
are also a means of building a
more resilient, more equitable,

00:37:58.430 --> 00:38:01.520
more prosperous,
more vibrant world.

00:38:01.520 --> 00:38:03.530
And I think when we
get locked in talking

00:38:03.530 --> 00:38:07.670
about just emissions, we lose
this bigger picture about what

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:12.620
the world that we're trying
to create actually looks like.

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:15.830
We already have the technical
capacity to achieve drawdown.

00:38:15.830 --> 00:38:18.350
I think that's a really,
really important takeaway

00:38:18.350 --> 00:38:19.740
from this book.

00:38:19.740 --> 00:38:22.250
So the question, then,
for all of us, I think,

00:38:22.250 --> 00:38:25.194
is how do we cultivate the
human capacity to get there?

00:38:25.194 --> 00:38:26.360
How do you stay in the work?

00:38:26.360 --> 00:38:28.820
How do you keep
making change happen?

00:38:28.820 --> 00:38:32.090
We have at least 100
ways in, as this book

00:38:32.090 --> 00:38:35.340
shows, to moving the
needle on global warming.

00:38:35.340 --> 00:38:38.960
So the question that I hope
it poses for all of you

00:38:38.960 --> 00:38:41.870
is, which one will you pick?

00:38:41.870 --> 00:38:43.790
Who might you work with?

00:38:43.790 --> 00:38:45.950
What talents might you deploy?

00:38:45.950 --> 00:38:50.390
There is such an incredible
opportunity for impact

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:52.730
and a role for everyone to play.

00:38:52.730 --> 00:38:57.410
The work to create this
book, and the ongoing work

00:38:57.410 --> 00:39:02.510
of keeping these models living
and evolving and improving,

00:39:02.510 --> 00:39:04.310
and keeping the
communication living

00:39:04.310 --> 00:39:07.280
and evolving and
improving, is complex.

00:39:07.280 --> 00:39:09.320
But actually, I think
the moral of the story

00:39:09.320 --> 00:39:12.380
is really, really simple,
which is that it's not game

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:16.430
over for climate change and
global warming and the planet.

00:39:16.430 --> 00:39:19.805
It's actually game on.

