00:43:33.230 --> 00:43:35.780
and my analysis
of what I thought

00:43:35.780 --> 00:43:37.850
was missing in the
climate movement

00:43:37.850 --> 00:43:39.720
and where it needed
to be stronger.

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:41.300
But also personally.

00:43:41.300 --> 00:43:46.100
I had been really tugged at
a sense of responsibility

00:43:46.100 --> 00:43:50.420
and possibility to
come back into making

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:52.980
an impact in this space.

00:43:52.980 --> 00:43:56.540
And so kind of the
combination of those two

00:43:56.540 --> 00:43:58.160
really just sang to me.

00:43:58.160 --> 00:44:00.770
So it's been fun to be--

00:44:00.770 --> 00:44:03.320
instead of sitting
in an academic seat

00:44:03.320 --> 00:44:05.030
kind of analyzing
the stories that we

00:44:05.030 --> 00:44:08.810
tell about the world and
our relationship to it--

00:44:08.810 --> 00:44:12.230
to actually be embedded in
this really amazing team

00:44:12.230 --> 00:44:14.700
that's doing the work
to shape those stories.

00:44:14.700 --> 00:44:15.730
SHERICE TORRES: Awesome.

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:19.100
So you talked about a
key legislative moment

00:44:19.100 --> 00:44:20.640
that was part of your journey.

00:44:20.640 --> 00:44:23.395
And I think everyone in here
is probably thinking about--

00:44:23.395 --> 00:44:24.770
and our live
stream-- is thinking

00:44:24.770 --> 00:44:27.710
about our current political
climate and the impact

00:44:27.710 --> 00:44:29.700
on the environmental
movement there,

00:44:29.700 --> 00:44:31.490
for the fact that
the word climate

00:44:31.490 --> 00:44:35.900
change is systematically
being removed from lots

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:38.090
of documents and papers.

00:44:38.090 --> 00:44:41.630
Would love to hear your
thoughts about climate change

00:44:41.630 --> 00:44:43.250
in this current
political environment.

00:44:43.250 --> 00:44:44.810
KATHARINE WILKINSON: Yeah.

00:44:44.810 --> 00:44:46.740
It does not feel
good to be here.

00:44:46.740 --> 00:44:54.690
I mean, I think everyone's
hope was that the second Bush

00:44:54.690 --> 00:44:56.690
Administration was going
to be the worst that we

00:44:56.690 --> 00:45:00.590
saw on this front, and that
we had hit at a turning point.

00:45:00.590 --> 00:45:01.910
Obviously that was wrong.

00:45:07.100 --> 00:45:09.320
So I want to be honest
about the bad news, which

00:45:09.320 --> 00:45:12.290
is that given the science
and given the timelines,

00:45:12.290 --> 00:45:15.470
we need every single part of
society pulling its weight

00:45:15.470 --> 00:45:18.050
to address this issue.

00:45:18.050 --> 00:45:21.320
We're not going to get
that from Washington.

00:45:21.320 --> 00:45:26.180
But the good news is that
actually, essentially all

00:45:26.180 --> 00:45:29.360
of the progress that's been
made in this country on climate

00:45:29.360 --> 00:45:32.090
has been done in the absence
of leadership in Washington.

00:45:32.090 --> 00:45:34.610
Even when you had the Obama
Administration pushing,

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:36.260
they were getting
thwarted and blocked,

00:45:36.260 --> 00:45:38.660
and a lot of those
initiatives have just

00:45:38.660 --> 00:45:39.980
been caught up in court.

00:45:39.980 --> 00:45:44.900
So actually the leaders on this,
cities, states, businesses,

00:45:44.900 --> 00:45:48.062
communities, have been leading,
they've been having an impact,

00:45:48.062 --> 00:45:49.520
and they're going
to keep doing it.

00:45:49.520 --> 00:45:53.300
And what we saw with the
announcement about the plan

00:45:53.300 --> 00:45:56.060
to pull out of the
Paris agreement

00:45:56.060 --> 00:46:02.360
was a doubling down both
from leaders in the US

00:46:02.360 --> 00:46:04.050
and also the rest of the world.

00:46:04.050 --> 00:46:05.300
And I think that was the fear.

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:08.660
If the US pulls out,
does everything crumble?

00:46:08.660 --> 00:46:12.330
And basically, everyone
said, yeah, no, we're in.

00:46:12.330 --> 00:46:17.760
And we're actually add
on to onto that bet.

00:46:17.760 --> 00:46:19.640
So I think that's
the great news.

00:46:19.640 --> 00:46:21.770
I think also we see
some really hopeful news

00:46:21.770 --> 00:46:23.630
around the economics.

00:46:23.630 --> 00:46:27.560
So a report just
recently came out

00:46:27.560 --> 00:46:29.930
that solar and wind
will be the cheapest

00:46:29.930 --> 00:46:33.440
form of electricity generation
in the world within three

00:46:33.440 --> 00:46:34.230
years.

00:46:34.230 --> 00:46:37.070
So they're already
at parity or cheaper

00:46:37.070 --> 00:46:38.600
in some parts of the world.

00:46:38.600 --> 00:46:44.630
But the cost declines that have
come around solar and turbine

00:46:44.630 --> 00:46:48.260
technology have happened so much
faster than anyone predicted.

00:46:48.260 --> 00:46:50.210
So I think we're
starting to see some

00:46:50.210 --> 00:46:55.650
of these kind of wind at our
back, I guess, of economics.

00:46:55.650 --> 00:46:59.780
And even probably a sort
of half-baked businessman

00:46:59.780 --> 00:47:01.430
in the White House
could figure out

00:47:01.430 --> 00:47:02.861
that those economics make sense.

00:47:02.861 --> 00:47:04.610
SHERICE TORRES: So you
talked a little bit

00:47:04.610 --> 00:47:08.480
about how climate
change has been

00:47:08.480 --> 00:47:09.710
positioned for individuals.

00:47:09.710 --> 00:47:12.410
It's about recycling
and electric cars

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:14.900
or using an electric bike.

00:47:14.900 --> 00:47:17.630
Talk to us about the relative
importance and different roles

00:47:17.630 --> 00:47:19.780
that individuals versus
collective action

00:47:19.780 --> 00:47:21.140
have to play in this.

00:47:21.140 --> 00:47:23.210
KATHARINE WILKINSON: Yeah.

00:47:23.210 --> 00:47:26.480
I think it's been a real miss
of the environmental movement

00:47:26.480 --> 00:47:33.120
to focus so much on
individual action.

00:47:33.120 --> 00:47:35.490
Look, individual action matters.

00:47:35.490 --> 00:47:38.540
I think it matters
more as a way to enact

00:47:38.540 --> 00:47:41.990
your values as it does impact.

00:47:41.990 --> 00:47:44.060
So I've been vegetarian
since I was 16.

00:47:44.060 --> 00:47:46.670
But for me, that's
partially a mechanism

00:47:46.670 --> 00:47:50.570
for reflecting on what
it is that I care about

00:47:50.570 --> 00:47:56.130
and reflecting on my ethic
at least three meals a day.

00:47:56.130 --> 00:47:58.910
So I think these things matter,
but collective action is really

00:47:58.910 --> 00:48:01.130
where the rubber hits the road.

00:48:01.130 --> 00:48:02.900
And that can be
collective action

00:48:02.900 --> 00:48:05.750
in the form of movements.

00:48:05.750 --> 00:48:07.970
You see really
incredible work being

00:48:07.970 --> 00:48:11.810
done by Bill McKibben and
350.org, which is focused more

00:48:11.810 --> 00:48:14.750
on how do we keep fossil
fuels in the ground, which

00:48:14.750 --> 00:48:17.240
is really important work.

00:48:17.240 --> 00:48:21.110
Citizens Climate Lobby has
built up a really incredible

00:48:21.110 --> 00:48:24.260
grassroots effort
to try and cultivate

00:48:24.260 --> 00:48:27.770
that political will in
every congressional district

00:48:27.770 --> 00:48:29.520
in the country.

00:48:29.520 --> 00:48:34.070
So you know, if that's a
place that you feel called

00:48:34.070 --> 00:48:38.420
to take action, I think
that's a really great way in,

00:48:38.420 --> 00:48:42.260
but also through business, and
also through neighborhoods.

00:48:42.260 --> 00:48:45.620
But we're probably never
going to see more than 5%

00:48:45.620 --> 00:48:50.930
or 10% of people really care and
really take voluntary action.

00:48:50.930 --> 00:48:55.260
So the question is, how
do you shift structures,

00:48:55.260 --> 00:48:59.330
and how do you shift bigger
institutions and organizations

00:48:59.330 --> 00:49:00.039
to make change?

00:49:00.039 --> 00:49:01.580
And what we see from
social movements

00:49:01.580 --> 00:49:04.130
is it doesn't take that
many people to pull together

00:49:04.130 --> 00:49:07.831
into a collective voice to
be able to move the needle.

00:49:07.831 --> 00:49:08.830
SHERICE TORRES: Awesome.

