So one of the texts
about global warming

00:55:17.180 --> 00:55:18.920
that I've read that
really concerns

00:55:18.920 --> 00:55:22.324
me is Bill McKibben's "Three
Numbers for Global Warming".

00:55:22.324 --> 00:55:23.990
I don't know if you're
familiar with it,

00:55:23.990 --> 00:55:26.027
but for people who
aren't, basically he

00:55:26.027 --> 00:55:27.110
talks about three numbers.

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:30.140
The first one is two degrees
Celsius is the consensus

00:55:30.140 --> 00:55:32.720
that scientists have agreed
that the temperature can rise

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:35.180
without horrific consequences.

00:55:35.180 --> 00:55:38.810
Then 500 and something
gigatons of carbon dioxide

00:55:38.810 --> 00:55:42.260
is how much carbon dioxide
that equivalents to.

00:55:42.260 --> 00:55:46.220
And then the last number, which
is when I got really terrified,

00:55:46.220 --> 00:55:52.700
is that, I think, 2,500, so
five times larger than the 500

00:55:52.700 --> 00:55:54.710
that we can emit
for two Celsius.

00:55:54.710 --> 00:55:58.070
So 2,500 is how much is
already planned in the economy

00:55:58.070 --> 00:56:00.860
to be emitted in I don't
know how many next years.

00:56:00.860 --> 00:56:02.900
So it's already in
companies' shares.

00:56:02.900 --> 00:56:06.770
It's already people
are going out and--

00:56:06.770 --> 00:56:09.200
it's oil that's already being
pulled out from the ground.

00:56:09.200 --> 00:56:12.020
So I guess coming
down to the question

00:56:12.020 --> 00:56:15.570
is, what are your
thoughts on that?

00:56:15.570 --> 00:56:18.380
And do you think we may
have reached a point where,

00:56:18.380 --> 00:56:20.870
even if we start doing
a bunch of actions,

00:56:20.870 --> 00:56:22.010
it might be too late?

