00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:33.920
The way I think
about it is, we don't

00:56:33.920 --> 00:56:36.740
have any option other
than to go really

00:56:36.740 --> 00:56:39.240
hard at solving the problem.

00:56:39.240 --> 00:56:43.000
If you say, well,
game over, then what?

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:45.800
You're going to just
give up on humanity?

00:56:45.800 --> 00:56:47.660
What do you do with that?

00:56:47.660 --> 00:56:51.710
And what I appreciate
from Bill McKibben

00:56:51.710 --> 00:56:54.950
and his work is, what
this has done for Bill is,

00:56:54.950 --> 00:56:58.220
he is on the front
lines of trying to keep

00:56:58.220 --> 00:57:01.520
fossil fuels in the ground.

00:57:01.520 --> 00:57:05.740
For me if I only think
about those numbers of,

00:57:05.740 --> 00:57:08.480
here's how much more we
can emit before we really

00:57:08.480 --> 00:57:12.500
turn this planet
into a disaster zone,

00:57:12.500 --> 00:57:14.600
and here's how much we're
planning on emitting,

00:57:14.600 --> 00:57:16.400
and even worse than
that, here's how much

00:57:16.400 --> 00:57:19.760
we could emit if we really went
for all of these fossil fuel

00:57:19.760 --> 00:57:20.900
resources--

00:57:20.900 --> 00:57:21.920
that's terrifying.

00:57:21.920 --> 00:57:27.920
And for me, that place of
terror leaves me feeling

00:57:27.920 --> 00:57:30.590
really frozen and paralyzed.

00:57:30.590 --> 00:57:33.560
And I think it's an
important part of the story

00:57:33.560 --> 00:57:36.290
to understand.

00:57:36.290 --> 00:57:40.610
And if you only
read that chapter,

00:57:40.610 --> 00:57:43.850
I think you miss
the bigger picture.

00:57:43.850 --> 00:57:46.359
Bill wrote a really great
article in "Rolling Stone"

00:57:46.359 --> 00:57:48.650
a few years ago called "Global
Warming's Terrifying New

00:57:48.650 --> 00:57:54.830
Math", which is just
totally terrifying.

00:57:54.830 --> 00:58:00.620
And I think we need to
be honest with ourselves

00:58:00.620 --> 00:58:04.310
about the potential
of what's ahead.

00:58:04.310 --> 00:58:11.030
But I think we have to be
really thoughtful about the rest

00:58:11.030 --> 00:58:13.280
of the conversation that
we're building in with that.

00:58:13.280 --> 00:58:15.950
So there was also a very
doom-and-gloomy piece

00:58:15.950 --> 00:58:19.430
just recently in
"New York" magazine,

00:58:19.430 --> 00:58:22.010
which my feeling is, if you're
going to do doom and gloom,

00:58:22.010 --> 00:58:22.850
do it like that.

00:58:22.850 --> 00:58:26.480
Just rip the bandage off
and just tell people.

00:58:26.480 --> 00:58:30.420
It's like, this is
how bad it could be.

00:58:30.420 --> 00:58:32.720
But what I didn't
like about that piece

00:58:32.720 --> 00:58:35.332
was at the end of
it, he says, yeah,

00:58:35.332 --> 00:58:37.040
but all these scientists
still have hope.

00:58:37.040 --> 00:58:40.340
And they have hope because
maybe there'll be a carbon tax

00:58:40.340 --> 00:58:43.430
and maybe we'll have some
geoengineering solutions.

00:58:43.430 --> 00:58:49.977
And to me, I don't have faith
in either of those, necessarily.

00:58:49.977 --> 00:58:51.560
I do have a lot of
faith in the things

00:58:51.560 --> 00:58:53.393
we're already doing
that are already working

00:58:53.393 --> 00:58:56.210
and our ability to
scale those things.

00:58:56.210 --> 00:58:58.670
Maybe we'll get some
extra help, but I

00:58:58.670 --> 00:59:00.800
don't think that's where
we should hang our hat.

00:59:00.800 --> 00:59:05.614
So these are my thoughts.

00:59:05.614 --> 00:59:07.530
We were talking about
this at lunch, actually.

00:59:07.530 --> 00:59:09.980
There's an amazing
Quaker thought

00:59:09.980 --> 00:59:11.780
leader named Parker
Palmer who talks

00:59:11.780 --> 00:59:15.650
about the tragic gap
and the work of staying

00:59:15.650 --> 00:59:18.710
in the tragic gap, which is
the space between the world

00:59:18.710 --> 00:59:22.920
as it is and the world as
it could be or should be.

00:59:22.920 --> 00:59:27.990
And it's really easy to flip out
into cynicism on the one side,

00:59:27.990 --> 00:59:30.900
or it's really easy
to flip out into kind

00:59:30.900 --> 00:59:35.250
of starry-eyed optimism,
like, gee whiz, you know,

00:59:35.250 --> 00:59:37.680
everything's always
getting better,

00:59:37.680 --> 00:59:41.400
and that there's work
to stay in the work.

00:59:41.400 --> 00:59:44.570
And I think that it's
different for different people.

00:59:44.570 --> 00:59:46.560
But if I only thought
about those numbers,

00:59:46.560 --> 00:59:50.550
I would only stay in
tragedy and cynicism,

00:59:50.550 --> 00:59:53.079
and I don't think I'd be
able to keep doing the work.

00:59:53.079 --> 00:59:55.620
SHERICE TORRES: And I think on
that point, we're at 2 o'clock

00:59:55.620 --> 00:59:56.870
and it's a great place to end.

00:59:56.870 --> 01:00:01.020
So let's keep on in
that gap doing the work,

01:00:01.020 --> 01:00:02.550
because through our actions--

01:00:02.550 --> 01:00:04.540
and collective actions,
more importantly,

01:00:04.540 --> 01:00:05.419
we can make a change.

01:00:05.419 --> 01:00:07.210
So Katharine, thank
you so much for coming.

01:00:07.210 --> 01:00:10.260
Thank you all for
attending and dialing in.

01:00:10.260 --> 01:00:12.110
[APPLAUSE]

